<h2 class="page">Superlative adjective in Russian</h2>

<h3 class="page-path">
<span class="int-links"><a href="/russian-grammar.html">Russian grammar</a>  <span class="int-arrow">--&gt;</span> Superlative adjective</span>
</h3>


<p>
Superlative adjectives, <strong>simple</strong> or <strong>compound</strong>, may be used both attributively and predicatively.
</p>

<h3 class="page-p">Simple superlative</h3>

<p>
The <dfn>simple superlative</dfn> is common in scientific and literary Russian; however, the same form is also used in colloquial Russian to express the speaker’s personal impression. 
</p>

<p>
The simple superlative is commonly used to express a value judgment on the part of the speaker and may be used when no comparison is made (English example: <em>a most interesting film</em>). You can translate the simple superlative into English as "a most", "a very", or "an extremely". The emphasis on the indefinite article indicates that the speaker has in mind one of many such superlative things. Note that like the compound superlative, the simple superlatve is declined.
</p>

<h4 class="page-pp">Formation of the simple superlative</h4>
<p>
Most adjectives form the simple superlative by means of the suffix -<span class="eg">ейш</span>- added to the stem of the adjective, and the endings -<span class="eg">ий</span>/-<span class="eg">ая</span>/-<span class="eg">ое</span>/-<span class="eg">ые</span>. 
</p>
<div class="ex-block-simple">
<strong>умный - умнейший</strong> &nbsp;&nbsp;smart - the smartest<br>
<strong>новый - новейший</strong> &nbsp;&nbsp;new - the newest
</div>

<p>
The suffix -<span class="eg">айш</span>-  is added to adjectives if their stem ends in the consonants <strong>г</strong>, <strong>к</strong>, and <strong>x</strong> which change to <span class="eg">ж</span>, <span class="eg">ч</span>, and <span class="eg">ш</span>, respectively.
</p>

<div class="ex-block-simple">
<strong>строгий - строжайший</strong> &nbsp;&nbsp;strict - the strictest<br>
<strong>высокий - высочайший</strong> &nbsp;&nbsp;high - the highest<br>
<strong>тихий - тишайший</strong> &nbsp;&nbsp;quiet - the quietest
</div>


<p>
Some adjectives form the simple superlative irregularly:
</p>

<div>
<span class="eg">плохой</span> <span class="egt">bad</span> - <span class="eg">худший</span> <br>
<span class="eg">маленький</span> <span class="egt">small</span> - <span class="eg">меньший</span><br>
<span class="eg">короткий</span> <span class="egt">short</span> - <span class="eg">кратчайший</span> <br>
<span class="eg">хороший</span> <span class="egt">good</span> - <span class="eg">лучший</span><br>
<span class="eg">тяжкий</span> <span class="egt">severe</span> - <span class="eg">тягчайший</span><br>
<span class="eg">дорогой</span> <span class="egt">dear</span> - <span class="eg">дражайший</span>
</div>

<p>
The simple superlative form of adjective declines similarly to the <a href="/russian-adjectives-declension.html#jsh-adj">long-form adjectives with stem ending in -ж, -ш, -ч, -щ</a>. 
</p>



<h3 class="page-p">Compound superlative</h4> 


<h4 class="page-pp">Formation of the compound superlative</h4>
<p>
The formation of the compound superlative is uncomplicated. It consists of the word <span class="eg">самый</span> <span class="egt">most</span> and the long form of the adjective. Both words agree in gender, number and case with the noun. 
</p>

<div class="ex-block-simple">
<strong>умный - самый умный</strong> &nbsp;&nbsp;smart - the smartest<br>
<strong>новый - самый новый</strong> &nbsp;&nbsp;new - the newest
</div>


<p>
Sometimes the words <span class="eg">наибóлее</span> <span class="egt">most</span> or <span class="eg">наимéнее</span> <span class="egt">least</span> can be used instead of <span class="eg">самый</span> to create superlative compound form.
</p>


<h3 class="page-p">Another way to form the superlative form</h3>

<p>
Instead of using the compound or simple superlative as described above, Russian conversation has a quick and easy way of expressing the superlative. This is to use the comparative plus the expressions <span class="eg">всех</span> <span class="egt">than anyone</span> or <span class="eg">всего</span> <span class="egt">than anything</span>:
</p>
<div class="ex-block-simple">
<strong>Он был умнее всех.</strong>  &nbsp;&nbsp;He was the smartest of all. 
</div>

